Note:
Runa Standard Library: Text Processing Utilities

Provides advanced text processing, formatting, and analysis utilities for Runa programs.

Idiomatic Runa code uses natural language operators and class-based APIs:
  Let wrapper be TextWrapper with width as 40
  Let wrapped_text be wrapper.wrap("This is a long text.")
  Let filled_text be wrapper.fill("This is a long text.")
  Let count be word_count("Hello world!")
:End Note

Class TextWrapper with:
    width as Integer
    initial_indent as String (default: "")
    subsequent_indent as String (default: "")
    expand_tabs as Boolean (default: true)
    replace_whitespace as Boolean (default: true)
    fix_sentence_endings as Boolean (default: false)
    break_long_words as Boolean (default: true)
    break_on_hyphens as Boolean (default: true)
    tabsize as Integer (default: 8)
    drop_whitespace as Boolean (default: true)

    Process called "wrap" that takes self and text as String returns List[String]:
        # Implementation: wrap text to lines of self.width
        Return wrapped_lines(text, self.width, self.initial_indent, self.subsequent_indent)

    Process called "fill" that takes self and text as String returns String:
        # Implementation: fill text to a single string
        Return filled_text(text, self.width, self.initial_indent, self.subsequent_indent)

Process called "dedent" that takes text as String returns String:
    Return remove_common_indentation(text)

Process called "indent" that takes text as String and prefix as String returns String:
    Return add_prefix_to_lines(text, prefix)

Process called "fill" that takes text as String and width as Integer returns String:
    Return fill_text(text, width)

Process called "shorten" that takes text as String and width as Integer returns String:
    Return shorten_text(text, width)

Process called "wrap" that takes text as String and width as Integer returns List[String]:
    Return wrap_text(text, width)

Process called "get_text_width" that takes text as String returns Integer:
    Return display_width(text)

Process called "justify" that takes text as String and width as Integer and justify_type as String returns String:
    Return justify_text(text, width, justify_type)

Process called "center" that takes text as String and width as Integer returns String:
    Return center_text(text, width)

Process called "ljust" that takes text as String and width as Integer returns String:
    Return left_justify_text(text, width)

Process called "rjust" that takes text as String and width as Integer returns String:
    Return right_justify_text(text, width)

Process called "word_count" that takes text as String returns Integer:
    Return count_words(text)

Process called "char_count" that takes text as String and include_spaces as Boolean (default: true) returns Integer:
    Return count_characters(text, include_spaces)

Process called "line_count" that takes text as String returns Integer:
    Return count_lines(text)

Process called "sentence_count" that takes text as String returns Integer:
    Return count_sentences(text)

Process called "paragraph_count" that takes text as String returns Integer:
    Return count_paragraphs(text)

Process called "readability_score" that takes text as String returns Float:
    Return flesch_reading_ease(text)

Process called "text_statistics" that takes text as String returns Dictionary[String, Any]:
    Return compute_text_statistics(text) 